[2]
Date: Thu, 6 Mar 97 14:47:10 GMT
From: D Stevenson <ds@tattoo.ed.ac.uk>
The Islamic year being of a different length to the solar year, or the year
of most [other] calendars, (? about 11 days shorter), the period of the Hajj
slowly moves through the different seasons of the solar year. This has
implications for health problems, certainly for heat-exhaustion among
pilgrims (addressed by the Saudi Arabian authorities) and also for infections.
---
David Stevenson,
Public Health Sciences
University of Edinburgh, Scotland.
e-mail: <ds@tattoo.ed.ac.uk>
